superEntry.entry:
raHFI c
raHFI (S, Msb, K, &c.) and raHFA, (Msb, * K,) the former of which is the more approved, (TA,) and some say raHaMCN↓, (S,) A mill; syn. TaAHuwnN: (Msb:) [and] a mill-stone; i. e. the great round stone with which one grinds: (TA:) of the fem. gender: (Zj, S, Msb, K:) dual of the first raHayaAni, (S, Msb, K,) and of the second raHawaAni, (Msb, * K,) and of the third, raHaAMni: (S:) the pl. (of pauc., S) of raHFI (Msb) [and of raHFA] is OaroHK and (of mult., S) OaroHaMCN, (S, Msb, K,) which latter is the pl. that is preferred accord. to IAmb, (Msb,) and ruHiIRN and riHiIRN, (Msb, K, TA,) with damm and with kesr (Msb, TA) to the r (Msb,) [for the last of which raHiIRN is substituted in the CK,] and OuroHiIRN, (K, TA,) with damm, and with kesr to the H and teshdeed to the I (TA,) [in the CK OaroHiIRN,] and OaroHiyapN, (Msb, K,) which is extr., (K,) said by AHát to be wrong, and by IAmb to be anomalous, and by Zj to be not allowable, (Msb,) in the T said to be as though it were a pl. pl., (TA,) or it is pl. of raHaMCN [and therefore regular]: (S:) the dim. is ruHayRapN↓. (Zj, Msb.) raHaA Alyadi [or raHaI Alyadi] signifies The hand-mill. (MA.) ― -b2- [Hence, A molar tooth, or grinder:] i. q. DirosN; (S, Msb, K;) pl. OaroHaMCN i. q. OaDoraAsN: (S:) [or rather] the OaroHaMC, also called the TawaAHin, are the twelve teeth, three on each side [above and below], next after the DawaAHik [or bicuspids]. (Zj, in his “ Khalk el-Insán. ”) ― -b3- [And app. A roller with which land is rolled to crush the clods; as being likened to a mill-stone: see 1 in art. xtm, near the end of the paragraph.] ― -b4- Stones: and a great rock, or mass of stone. (TA.) ― -b5- A round piece of ground, rising above what surrounds it, (S, K,) about as large in extent as a mile: (K:) pl. OaroHaMCN: (K, TA:) or this latter, i. e. the pl., signifies pieces of rugged ground, less than mountains, round, and rising above what surrounds them: (M, TA:) or raHFA mina AlOaroDi means a round and rugged place [or piece of ground] among sands: (Sh, TA:) or a large and rugged [elevation such as is termed] qaArap or Oakamap, round, rising above what surrounds it, not spreading upon the surface of the earth, nor producing herbs, or leguminous plants, nor trees. (ISh, TA.) ― -b6- A round cloud; [as being likened to a mill-stone;] (A in art. rjH:) or so raHaI saHaAbK. (S.) ― -b7- The kirokirap [or callous protuberance upon the breast] of a camel; (T, S, K;) so called because of its roundness: (TA:) pl. OaroHaMCN: (K:) which likewise signifies the callous protuberances upon the knees of the camel. (T, TA.) ― -b8- The foot (firosin) of the camel and of the elephant: pl. OaroHaMCN. (M, K.) ― -b9- A daAYirap [app. meaning a circling border] around the nail. (TA.) ― -b10- The breast, or chest: pl., as in the other senses following, OaroHaMCN. (K.) ― -b11- Spinage, or spinach; (M, K;) because of the roundness of its leaves. (TA.) ― -b12- (tropical:) A collective body of the members of a household. (ISd, K, TA.) ― -b13- (tropical:) An independent tribe: (K, TA:) OaroHaMCN (which is its pl., K, TA) signifies (tropical:) independent tribes, that are in no need of others. (S, TA.) ― -b14- (assumed tropical:) A large number of camels, crowding, or pressing, together; (S, K, TA;) also called TaHRaAnapN: (S, TA:) or raHaA AlUibili means the collective herd of the camels: and in like manner, raHaA Alqawomi the collective body of the people, or party. (ISk, TA.) ― -b15- raHaI Alqawomi signifies [also] (tropical:) The chief of the people, or party. (T, S, M, K, TA.) [It is added in the TA that 'Omar Ibn-El-Khattáb was called raHaI AlHarobi, as though meaning (assumed tropical:) The chief of war; because of his warlike propensities: but it seems from what here follows, as well as from what precedes, that this may be a mistranscription, for raHaI Alqawomi or raHaI AlEarabi.] ― -b16- raHaI AlHarobi signifies (tropical:) The most vehement part [or the thickest] of the fight; syn. HawomatuhaA: (S, Msb:) in the K it is said that AlrRaHaI signifies Hawomapu AlHarobi, and muEoZamuhu; as also AlmaroHaI↓: but it seems that there is an omission;
for AlHrb is [generally] fem., and in the M it is said that raHaI Almawoti signifies muEoZamuhu [app. meaning the main stress, or the thickest, of death in battle]. (TA.) In a saying relating to 'Alee's having made an end of Aljamali maroHay↓, this expression is expl. by A 'Obeyd as meaning The place around which revolved the thickest of the fight (AlmawoDiEu AlRaciy daArato Ealayohi raHay AlHarobi) [in the Battle of the Camel]. (TA.) And daArato Ealayohi raHay Almawoti [which may be rendered (assumed tropical:) The main stress of death beset him round about] means death befell him. (Msb, TA.)

ruqRN c
ruqRN Shallow, applied to water; or shallow water; (maMCN raqiyqN↓; IDrd, K, TA;) not copious, or not abundant; (IDrd, TA;) in a sea, or great river, or in a valley; (IDrd, K, TA;) as also raqRN↓;
(K;) and so ruqaAriqN↓. (IDrd, K.) ― -b2- See also raqaAqN.
